Honda Worldwide | Motor Sports | MotoGP | Honda Riders Close Up | MotoGP Jack Miller, Drive Estrella Galicia 0,0 Marc VDS(RC213V)

























World news
Products & Technology
Motor Sports
Environment
Investor Relations
About Honda
Honda World Links







Honda Worldwide Home
Motor Sports
MotoGP
2017 Topics
Honda Riders Close Up
MotoGP Jack Miller, Drive Estrella Galicia 0,0 Marc VDS














MotoGP Jack Miller, Estrella Galicia 0,0 Marc VDS




Profile

Date of Birth
18/01/1995
Birthplace
Australia
Height/Weight
175cm・70kg
Team (Machine)
Estrella Galicia 0,0 Marc VDS(RC213V)
Results of 2016
18th MotoGP World Championship









Vol.2
At the halfway mark of the 2017 championship, Team Estrella Galicia 0,0 Marc VDS rider Jack Miller was 12th in the championship standings. Apart from two races he had finished empty-handed, at the Spanish Grand Prix and in Catalunya, the 22-year-old Australian scored championship points in seven races. 12th position at the halfway mark for him, is his best result of his three seasons in MotoGP racing.
From Rounds 3, the Grand Prix of the Americas, through 5, the French Grand Prix, Miller consistently placed himself in Q2. In France, he started the race weekend clocking the fastest lap time. The following day, in FP4, Miller had a scary high-speed crash at Turn 2, but fortunately escaped without injury. In qualifying, he set the 11th quickest lap time to start the race from Row 4. He finished the race in a brilliant eighth place, despite being battered and bruised. 
“I was a little fortunate today with some other riders having problems, but in racing you have to be in it at the finish to get the best result and that’s what we did. Considering my physical condition, I think I rode a good race despite struggling to pick up on exiting the corner. I’m happy to be back in the top ten both in the race and the points, but it’s only early in the season so there's still a lot of work to do. I had a good weekend going until my crash in FP4, so now I’ll go home and rest my body and get ready to come back stronger in Mugello.”
In the next race, the Italian Grand Prix at the Mugello circuit, Miller finished 15th and gained one championship point. Then one week later at the Barcelona-Catalunya circuit for the seventh round of the season, a rumor circulated in the paddock that Miller would ride in the Suzuka 8hours race in late July. When asked about it, Miller did not confirm anything but said, “Yeah, I mean I would like to, but we cannot say anything just yet." He was non-commital, avoiding dismissal of the speculation.
“I think the announcement will be soon. It's been something that I really wanted to do ever since I came back to Honda in 2015. Happy enough...maybe be going there this year would be good."
















Just before the race weekend for the Dutch TT, the announcement was made: Jack Miller would take part in the 40th Suzuka 8hours race, joining the MuSASHi RT HARC-PRO. Honda team, alongside Takumi Takahashi and Takaaki Nakagami.
After Friday’s free practice sessions, Miller finally revealed his feelings with a broad smile. 
"I’m really excited to get the opportunity to race over there. It’s something I’ve wanted to do for a while and to go over there with one of the best teams, it’s a big opportunity for me and I look forward to the challenge. It’s going to be a long, hot summer for me but it’s going to be good!"
Last year at TT Circuit Assen, Miller had won his first premier class race in dramatic style. For this year’s race, despite a lower starting grid position of 13th, he finished the race 6th, which was the best result for him so far this season.
“The first lap was not good, from my grid position I got stuck on the outside through all the right-hand turns and lost time, but once the group flattened out I got up to tenth in a group with Dani and Cal. I was a having a nice fight with Dani and then the rain came. I kept my pace to keep up the temperature in the slick tires, and pushed through to sixth. With more risks I might have been able to challenge for the podium but I wanted the points, this was a good result for me.”
At the German Grand Prix, Miller finished 15th. For the fist half of the 2017 season, Miller scored championship points in seven out of nine races, placing him 12th in the championship.
“Sitting at the moment, I'm twelfth in the standings, I would've liked to be inside the top 10, but you know, a couple of mistakes here and there cost us. But anyway, 41 points is decent to me, and showed well that we've improved this year. I am looking forward to making another, let's say 60 points in the second half of the season, which would be nice.”
Right after the race, Miller flew to Japan to join two days of Suzuka 8hours testing, on July 5 and 6. In the following week from July 11 to 13, he participated in official tests, demonstrating his ability to quickly adapt, living up to his potential as a world premier class rider.
“It was always a big question mark coming into this race because I never tested Superbikes, so I didn't know how I would perform on the bike. But now, we adapted to it very quickly. I feel from the beginning we've been quite fast. Not having many tests, but I'm not so far from my teammate. I think we have a very very strong team between us, which also helped to boost my confidence. We are all consistent, all of our long runs have been very good, so it seems that we will start a good race weekend. And of course, I've come here to win!”
Now that the long summer weekend at Suzuka has begun for Jack Miller, his best moments should be just around the corner.








 Vol.1











